\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 The basic structure\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 CCHP is a 
\f1\b three-rung distance ladder
\f0\b0  that runs in parallel to SH0ES, with the same overall architecture but different choices at each rung:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Rung 1 (anchors)
\f0\b0 : NGC 4258 maser + LMC DEBs (and historically SMC, MW field giants) 
\f1\b Rung 2 (calibrators)
\f0\b0 : TRGB stars (and now JAGB stars too) in SN Ia host galaxies 
\f1\b Rung 3 (Hubble flow)
\f0\b0 : SN Ia in calibrator hosts + Hubble-flow SN Ia\
The methodological substitution is at rung 2: 
\f1\b TRGB and JAGB instead of Cepheids
\f0\b0 . Same anchors at the bottom, same SN Ia at the top \'97 just different stellar tracers in the middle. This makes CCHP and SH0ES the cleanest "head-to-head" comparison in the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  field, with the discrepancy between them isolating systematics in the stellar-distance methodology.\
The key conceptual move is using 
\f1\b Pop-II tracers
\f0\b0  (old, low-mass stars) instead of 
\f1\b Pop-I tracers
\f0\b0  (young, massive stars). The motivation, articulated by Wendy Freedman and Barry Madore from the start of the program in ~2010, was that:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 TRGB stars exist in 
\f1\b all galaxy types
\f0\b0 , including the smooth halos of E/S0 hosts where Cepheids cannot be found.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 TRGB photometry is done in 
\f1\b uncrowded halo fields
\f0\b0 , eliminating the crowding/blending concerns that plague Cepheid photometry in dusty inner spiral disks.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The TRGB is 
\f1\b calibrated empirically
\f0\b0  on globular cluster CMDs and can be cross-checked across many populations, with weak metallicity dependence.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The TRGB tip magnitude is 
\f1\b insensitive to age and metallicity
\f0\b0  in the I-band \'97 this is the key empirical claim that makes TRGB a competitive distance indicator.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 If this all works as advertised, TRGB is a methodologically simpler distance measurement than Cepheids: just identify the tip of the red giant branch in a CMD and read off the apparent magnitude. No period-luminosity relation, no metallicity correction, no inclination, no individual-star photometric variability monitoring required.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

